The commentators in general assume that Horace could not have taken the liberty to refer to Terentia in the con- cluding lines, “ Manum puella,'' &C., and that the poem was therefore written before Maecenas’s marriage, probably A.U.C. 719 or 720. Ritter, on the contrary, denounces with much indignation the idea that Horace could impute the inde- corum of so familiar an intercourse with a freedwoman to a man of the grave occupations and dignified position of Maecenas, and insists on applying “puella ’' to Terentia, in which case the poem would be written shortly after the

marriage of Maecenas, which Ritter chooses to date, A.U.C. 72 5 (i. e.‚ a year after Franke's date for the publication of
